title: For Sale/Trade:  Rare PTR 91 "Special Edition"  308 16" Rifle w/ custom Trigger Pack
postcontent:
I am considering selling or trading my rare PTR 91 factory "Special Edition" rifle.  It has a 16" match grade bull barrel, the wide triangle HK foregrip, and welded top rail.  I added a custom trigger pack from Bill Springfield that lowered the trigger pull from about 8lbs to ~4.5lbs (I have the original trigger pack as well).  I also added a simple riser rail, and a Leupold VX 3x9-40 scope.  That is an option, and can be removed before the sale/trade.

Now, for the "Special Edition" part.  This was part of a custom group of weapons put out by PTR.  I challenge you to search PTR's website for this rifle....you will not find it.  The A3R is close, but that has the 18" bull barrel.  I was lucky enough to grab one of these.  I would rather have this foregrip than the vented aluminum/poly ones.  This remindes me more of a true older HK rifle.

I got to take this to the range once.  I was working up some 308 loads for a bolt action, and took this along.  I had about 10 minutes left at the end of the session, and unloaded the 3 10 round HK magazines I have.  It shoots VERY nice.  Not much recoil (since it is not the lightest gun in the world...9 lbs without the scope or magazines, close to 15 fully loaded).  It didn't give me a chance to zero the scope, but I just wanted to get a feel for the rifle itself.  

I don't NEED to sell this.  I am just seeing what is out there, and what offers are to be made.  NO low ball offers!  This is not your "off the shelf" PTR.  If you are worried about it being an HK clone....go read up on the PTR.  It is made with true HK tooling from the Portugal HK factor that closed down.  It is the closest thing to a true HK that you can get for under $3k.





This has been to the range once, and about 30 rounds through it.  I had multiple weapons at the range, and had just enough time to go through my pre-loaded 3 10 round HK magazines.

title: For Sale/Trade:  POF AR-15 Custom Rifle
postcontent:
I am considering selling/trading my modified/custom POF AR-15 rifle.  This started life as a POR P415 16" rifle that cost over $2000.  I then started modifying it to make it the lightest, most accurate weapon possible.  

I built a custom upper with the M4E1 Enhanced Aero upper receiver that integrated the foregrip into the upper receiver.  The barrel is a Daniel Defense Hammer Forged 14.5" barrel.  It is finished with a Surefire 5.56 Muzzle Brake.  I have a low profile, slip on, gas block, and VooDoo Lifecoat gas tube.  This goes to a Nickel Boron (NiB) Bolt Carrier Group.  The charging handle is a Rainier Arms (AXTS) Ambidexterous handle.  

For the lower, the only thing I added was a JP Piston Buffer.  It adds just a little bit of weight vs a stock buffer, but it reduces recoil so much, it makes followup shots 10x easier.  The rest of the POF lower features a built-in ambi bolt release (built into the lower receiver), an ambi safety, KNS anti-rotate trigger pins, a Magpul grip and buttstock, and topping it off, the POF trigger group at 4.5 lbs.

Optics wise, I have a real Aimpoint T-1 Micro 2 MOA dot sight (LaRue QD mount) with a Vortex 3x magnifier with "flip to the side" capabilities.  It gives rapid acquisition with just the T-1, or more accurate, longer range, shots with the magnifier in place.

As I said, this is by far the best AR platform I have ever shot.  I have at least 100 ARs over the years, and this is the best of everything I have learned.  Accuracy: Check!  Light Weight: Check!  Reduced Recoil: Check!  This has it all, and then some!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Ar-15 with 2 Uppers 20" 5.56 Long Range, and 14.5" 300 Blackout
postcontent:
I am considering selling/trading my Custom Built 20" AR with my 14.5" 300 Blackout Upper.  I can and WILL split these up if requested!!!!

Lets start with the lower receiver first.  It is an Aero Precision lower, with a Timney Gold Skeletonized 4.5lb Match trigger.  It is a single stage match trigger with the best break of any trigger I have ever had.  It is held in place with KNS anti-rotation trigger pins.  The Takedowns are Yankee Hill EZ takedowns.  A BAD Ambi safety, Magpul Battery Asssist Device, and Magpul trigger guard are also installed.  The buttstock is a Magpul UBR.  

The upper is a POF upper receiver with a Wilson Combat 5.56 marked ejection port cover.  The Foregrip is a Yankee Hill Todd Jarrett Competition 15" Extended Rifle Length with a Yankee Hill endcap is installed.  The barrel is a BCM 20" 1:7 twist Competition barrel.  I am not sure if they even make this barrel anymore, I have had it about 2 years.  I don't remember who makes the muzzle brake.....  The bolt is a Nickel Boron (NiB) Bolt Carrier Group, and a Rainier Arms (AXTS) ambidextrous charging handle.

The Optic is a Nikon M-223 3x12-42 scope.  It is mounted on a quick release riser with Nikon rings.

The 300 Blackout Upper is build on a M4E1 Aero Enhanced Upper with a 9" foregrip.  The Enhanced Upper intergrates the upper receiver and foregrip into a solid mount platform.  The barrel is a Rainier Arms Match 300 Blackout 14.5" barrel with a pistol length gas system.  The barrel is topped with a Yankee Hill flash hider.  It has its own Rainier Arms (AXTS) charging handle, but shares the same bolt as the 20" AR (since they use the same bolt anyway).  The optic is a Vector 1x6-28 First Focal Plane scope. This means that when you zoom, the reticle zooms with you.  It is dual illuminated red/green.

The 20" rifle will shoot sub MOA all day, and the 300 Blackout is capable of being fired with Super or Sub Sonic ammo.  The 20" 5.56 upper has about 200 rounds through it, just enough to get the scope zero'd and shoot some 30 round groups.  Infact, when I had it at the indoor range about a month ago, I was shooting tighter groups with an AR @ 100 yards than either guy beside me.  One had a 308 bolt, the other had a benchrested AR @ 50 yards.  Both were very impressed.  The 14.5" 300 blackout was just recently built.  It has about 50 rounds through it, 30 building a Super Sonic load, and 20 building a Sub Sonic Load.  My intent was to register the lower as a SBR, and put a 7.5" barrel on the 300 Blackout, then add a suppressor.  The 9" upper would put part of the suppressor under the handguard giving an much better look.

I don't NEED to sell this, and I don't NEED help selling this.  I am just looking to see what is out there and what offers I get.  No LOW BALL offers.  I build these almost daily, and know what is in them.

title: For Sale:  Ruger MkIII 22/45 Target model #10107
postcontent:
Standard Mark III 22/45 Target model #10107 with a 5.5” barrel and molded grip handles.

Bought new only a couple of months ago. About 120 rounds through it so far with no malfunctions of any kind. I’ve been very happy with it and I’m only selling because I want a 22/45 “lite” model with a threaded barrel and this has to go to help fund that.

Comes with all original factory stuff (box, manual, lock, 2 magazines, scope rail). Also, before I ever fired it I removed the magazine disconnect and in its place installed a TandemKross steel hammer bushing made specifically for these guns. For those who don’t know, the magazine disconnect is supposedly a “safety feature” that prevents the trigger from being pulled without a magazine inserted. In the case of Ruger 22/45s, however, this also makes the trigger very gritty, it prevents the magazines from dropping free when released, and it makes disassembly/reassembly way more more troublesome than it already is for these models. Removal of the disconnect and replacement with the hammer bushing makes a world of difference and I believe is an almost necessary upgrade.

It still has the manual safety, however if you’re more comfortable with the original factory magazine disconnect in place, I have the original parts and can easily replace them in a few minutes while you wait. Even if you want to keep it like it is for now, I’ll include the original parts with the gun.

$260. In Murray/Calloway County area. Face to face transfer. You know the rules... Kentucky resident and don't be a bad guy.

title: For Sale:  Stainless Steel Refinish Service
postcontent:
Increase the value of your stainless firearm with our refinishing service. We specialize in S&W Gen 2 and 3 finishes and can accurately match the factory finish. Our service is for any stainless firearm or stainless part of any kind you may wish to restore to like new condition. We also refinish stainless rifle parts and barrels depending on length.

We offer satin finish, matte/frosted finish and brushed finishes (requires hand working) for both pistols and revolvers. We do not offer polishing of bright parts.

The auction price is to refinish one pistol slide, pistol frame, pistol barrel or similar small stainless part. Price does not include hand working for a brushed finish or to eliminate cuts, scratches, agency markings or gouges. Parts need to be delivered "detail stripped" as we do not offer gunsmith or dis-assembly services. Ask your local gunsmith for assistance if you are unable to detail strip your part.

Price for pistol frame/slide/barrel combination is $70 and includes small parts such as slide release, safety levers and other small parts.

Due to the low volume for our service, we only schedule once per month.  Email us for our next scheduled run date.

Since each job is different, email us with your expectations as to the style of finish you require.

Slides and non-FFL parts may be shipped direct. Frames and receivers must be shipped to our FFL affiliates.

Return shipping is actual USPS postage.  When sending FFL required parts, please add a $10 FFL handling fee. You can estimate return shipping by verifying the size "Flat Rate" box your part will fit or call us for a quote. Add for insurance over the standard USPS $50.00.

We offer an FFL/Gunsmith discount.

title: For Sale:  SMITH & WESSON MODEL 745,  .45 CAL SEMI-AUTO MATCH/COMPETITION
postcontent:
This 745 is a single action only version of S&W's original full-size, DA/SA .45--the 645.  The 745 was designed specifically for IPSC (International Practical Shooting Confederation) a shooting sport designed from the start to  promote, maintain, and advance practical marksmanship.

Much like the Colt Gold Cup, this was designed as a target gun, and as such it excels.  The trigger is exceptionally short and light, with a lightning quick reset.  The trigger stop can be used to further tune trigger travel to an absolute minimum.
The slide-mounted safety is a hammer block only--flipping the safety down blocks the hammer from the firing pin, but does not act as a lock.  This gun cannot be considered "cocked and locked" like a 1911, however this gun was never meant for daily carry, only target and sport shooting use. 
Because of the superior trigger and barrel muzzle/slide lock up the 745 generally displays better accuracy than its' contemporary Gold Cup counterparts.   The 745 is an exceptionally accurate gun aimed at shooting sports and informal target shooting.
This 745 will easily put a box of 50 rounds into a two inch hole at 25 yards, shooting from a sandbag  rest. The 745 was made in small numbers (5000-6000 total).
Befitting a target/sport shooting gun, the 745 sports an oversize and aggressively checkered magazine release as well as an adjustable trigger stop.
The extremely light and short single action trigger can almost be adjusted until no pre or over travel can be felt.  In short, this trigger almost can be made to behave like the click of a computer mouse.
The full trigger pull weight on my 745 is around three pounds.  That pull weight is from the factory without any additional work.  I cannot describe just how great this trigger is to use, it must be experienced to be appreciated. Grips are pachmayr, and pistol comes with original box, papers, two 8 round clips and 17 rounds of ammo. The 745 is in great condition, and I doubt that I've put more than 2 boxes of ammo through it.

There are pretty popular at matches and seem to be almost as popular as the drastically more expensive Benelli M2.

This has received several modifications for use in 3 gun that make it both easier to load, and more reliable and will work great for other sports as well.
